	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Price volatility financial constraints and declining levels of support set context for CAP debate </h1>

			
			<h4>
												15 October 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At their meeting from 24 to 25 September, the EU Agriculture and Fisheries Council took forward the discussions on further reform of the CAP, with a focus on the draft regulation on market management tools and safety nets. According to Cyprus’ Minister of Agriculture, Sofoclis Aletraris, many member state delegations considered that EC safety-net proposals struck ‘the right balance’, but with room for improvement. Many member states supported a modification of the mechanism for establishing reference prices, although some took the view that the current level of reference prices was ‘sufficient’.</p><p>In the run-up to the meeting, EU farmers’ organisation Copa-Cogeca ‘called on EU farm ministers to step up EU measures to manage the market…in order to ensure a balanced market situation’. The Copa-Cogeca Secretary-General Pekka Pesonen argued that farmers faced serious challenges in managing rising production costs, and that in this context it was ‘vital that market management measures enable producers to cope during periods of low market prices and/or rapid increases in costs’.</p><p>Copa-Cogeca called for market management measures to be reinforced and updated. It was argued that ‘the EU intervention price for butter and skimmed milk powder…must be updated to take account of the higher production costs farmers face.’ A call was also made for an extension of the intervention period to cover the whole year, given the increasing influence of global dairy price developments on EU price trends. Concerns were also expressed about the impact of any revision of the EU biofuel mandate on oilseed, cereals and sugar markets in the EU.</p><p>Meanwhile, according to a recent report, the OECD Secretariat has reported that agricultural support programmes in 2011 were at ‘a record low’, of $252 billion globally. The EU was reported to have ‘reduced its level of support to 20% of farm income’.</p><p>Analysts have suggested that the reported global levels were a result of the high global food prices rather than substantive reforms undertaken by OECD governments. (5) Indeed, ICTSD has pointed out that the stalling of the WTO negotiations has ‘eased the pressure’ for change in agricultural subsidy policies. However, some exporting country officials see improved disciplines as an ‘insurance’ against times when agricultural prices fall and farmers call for more support.</p><p>Overall, OECD officials highlighted in the report that ‘support which distorts production and trade still represents about half of the total.’&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
