<a href="http://www.thepigsite.com/swinenews/31009/significant-progress-on-ag-policy-made" target="_self">http://www.thepigsite.com/swinenews/31009/significant-progress-on-ag-pol...</a></p><p><i>Thecattlesite.com</i>, ‘Measures to manage markets must be stepped up’, 26 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thedairysite.com/news/39990/measures-to-manage-markets-must-be-stepped-up" target="_self">http://www.thedairysite.com/news/39990/measures-to-manage-markets-must-b...</a></p><p>OECD, ‘Support to agriculture at historic lows says OECD’, press release, 24 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.trademarksa.org/news/support-agriculture-historic-lows-says-oecd" target="_self">http://www.trademarksa.org/news/support-agriculture-historic-lows-says-oecd</a></p><p>ICTSD, ‘Subsidies smaller share of farm income, OECD says’, <i>Bridges Weekly Trade News Digest</i>, Volume 16, Number 32, 26 September 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/146118/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/146118/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In an era of heightened global price volatility, the market management measures to be used by the EU post-2014 can have important implications for ACP producers. To the extent that EU market management measures insulate EU producers from price downturns, this can mean that the effects of necessary global adjustments are shifted onto the shoulders of non-EU producers, including those in the ACP. Developments during the last major EU dairy market crisis are illustrative in this regard (see <i>Agritrade</i> articles, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/USDA-review-reveals-continued-growth-in-EU-skimmed-milk-powder-exports" target="_blank">USDA review reveals continued growth in EU skimmed-milk powder exports</a>’, 4 December 2011 and ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/The-dairy-sector-and-the-EU-s-evolving-safety-net-policy" target="_blank">The dairy sector and the EU’s evolving safety-net policy</a>’, 28 November 2011).</p><p>The trend in EU policy is towards more targeted and effective safety nets to insulate farmers during price downturns, since the policy objective of avoiding sharp declines in agricultural production in the EU can then be achieved at lower overall cost to the EU budget. The question arises: can effective safety-net measures for EU agricultural producers be designed which avoid ‘adjustment displacement’ to non-EU producers, particularly those in the ACP?</p><p>This may require sector-specific flanking measures and country-/region-specific agreements with ACP governments on the use of export licensing and export refund policy tools where efforts are under way to develop domestic agricultural production in the same products (e.g. managed trade arrangements for the export of EU milk powder to ACP countries seeking to improve the functioning of domestic milk supply chains).</p><p>This, however, would reach beyond the current EC approach to managing the external effects of a reformed CAP, and would amount to an implicit acknowledgement of the trade consequences of reformed EU domestic agricultural policy measures.</p>
		</div>
		
